things.what: Transforms Plastic Bottles into rPET flake
things.description:
Environmental Cleaning Solutions S.A. (ECSSA) is a recycling facility in Port au Prince, Haiti which collects and processes recyclable products; specifically PET, HDPE, LDPE, Tin, OCC, and Aluminum. 

ECSSA was founded in 2010 by Edouard Carrie. Ed believes strongly in the potential that recycling can have on his home nation and he is proud to have grown ECSSA to an internationally recognized company.

At ECSSA, plastic PET bottles are sent through a grinding line, producing rPET flake, which is exported to the U.S. for further processing.

Currently, ECSSA employs 24 Haitians at their Port au Prince facility.

Most of his clients bring recyclables to Metalfa every day. Rigoberto employs 11 people, including his son, Walter, and his daughter, Eunice.

"I love the impact I have on the environment. There are people in my community who depend on me. It's (recycling) important for the country. There are not many jobs, this provides a good job." - Rigoberto Alfaro

"Not only are we making money, but we're cleaning our country. I can see the change across my city."

things.name: Sixto Portillo
things.description:
Sixto is one of the most optimistic entrepreneurs we work with. He runs two collection centers with hopes of opening a third soon. He supports 60 collectors that come to sell him recyclables every day while employing 9 individuals between his two centers.

His daughter and grand daughter stopped by to visit after school the afternoon we were there. He is a proud grandfather and a savvy business man.

"I like everything about my job. It's a family business, but I have Sunday off so I can rest. I know the names of all my collectors, if a week goes by and they don't come, I'll go visit them to make sure they're ok. This is how they support their families, this is their way of life. We all live in the same environment, it's important to keep it clean." - Sixto Portillo

things.name: Jose Alberto Aguilar
things.description:
After five years, Jose has grown his recycling business to support 65 collectors and 4 employees, including 2 of his sons. He got into the business after seeing the success his brother had in recycling. He has three sons, 2 have graduated school and work with him to save for University, the youngest is still in school.

"Recycling is good for the community. It's helping to keep the neighborhood clean, which is very important. It's how I provide income for my family." - Jose Alberto Aguilar

"There's been a positive change here because of recycling."

things.name: Amilcar and Blanca Miranda
things.description:
Husband and Wife duo, Amilcar and Blanca own two collection center locations and have been suppliers to INVEMA for 21 years.

They have 30 regular collectors and also own 2 trucks, which they send around the city for pick ups. They employ 7 others between the 2 centers and their centers sent all five of their kids to university.

"We've made our life out of this. I'm proud that because of this job my kids have studied  and worked. I built my house and bought cars and trucks from this work. I like everything about this job." - Amilcar Miranda

things.name: Manuel Garcia
things.description:
Manuel Garcia (wearing the orange t shirt in the photo above) has been running a recycling center along with his two sisters and brother, for the past 15 years.

In addition to the siblings, they employ three other people at their center, while providing income for 45 collectors in their neighborhood. Before opening this center, Manuel was unemployed - he saw an opportunity not only for himself, but as a way to help the unemployment situation in Honduras. They have been expanding since they started, and the main goal of the family is to continue to grow the business.

"There's been a big change since we started (recycling). People have the ability to change their lives and it's a job that pays well. Bottles were covering the streets, now they're not. There's money in the streets!" - Manuel Garcia

things.name: Paulene Fanor
things.description: Paulene is a widow who has 3 children. She is the sister of a very productive woman entrepreneur called Nancie, who is living in Les Cayes, south side of Haiti. Fanor did not know nothing about what she could do with plastic bottles till her sister, Nancie explained to her what it is and how she is making money through it. Paulene has 2 full-time employees and 20 individuals collectors. She is mentored by Nancie, her sister.

things.name: Vilner Geffrard
things.description: Vilner Jecrois is living in Port-au-Prince. He is married and has one kid with his wife. Before getting into the plastic business he was selling metal to a facility and was a taptap driver. he gets into the plastic business in 2013. Ever since, he is a boss. He has 2 part-time and 2 full-time employees, and 40 individuals. Vilner has his own truck to ensure transportation. Also, he uses his truck to ensure transportation for other suppliers. His center is well-managed is among the most productive of the chain.

things.name: Emmanuel Jolivar
things.description: Jolivar is in the business in 2010 where he was selling metal to a facility. When he saw there was a good opportunity in the plastic, he got into it in 2013. He is living with his wife and his kid in Port-au-Prince. He has 3 full-time employees, and 30 individuals. He has another collection center in the centre ville. He is a very productive center owner. "This business is my life, my days," he quoted.

Jean Rico is living in Carrefour with his wife and 4 children. Jean Rico is a direct victim of the 2010 earthquake. He was living in a camp under a tent when he saw people collecting plastic and all in a sudden decided get into it. He started as center owner in 2012. Plastic business is his only income source. "There are plenty ways to earn one's life; plastic business is my only way," he stated.

The 7 children and the wife of Vertu depend on plastic bottles business. Vertu has been doing recycling since 1990. He was selling metal. His daughter is the one that is in charge to keep the ledger of the business. "I want my children to understand what I do for the family,' he stated.
